78 /// Mass of a block. ----
79 /// ----
80 /// This class implements a sort of fixed-point fraction always between 0.0 and ----
81 /// 1.0. getMass() == std::numeric_limits::max() indicates a value of ----
82 /// 1.0. ----
83 /// ----
84 /// Masses can be added and subtracted. Simple saturation arithmetic is used, ----
85 /// so arithmetic operations never overflow or underflow. ----
86 /// ----
87 /// Masses can be multiplied. Multiplication treats full mass as 1.0 and uses ----
88 /// an inexpensive floating-point algorithm that's off-by-one (almost, but not ----
89 /// quite, maximum precision). ----
90 /// ----
91 /// Masses can be scaled by \a BranchProbability at maximum precision. ----
92 class BlockMass { ----
93 uint64_t Mass = 0; ----
94 ----
95 public: ----

98 ----

100 ----
101 static BlockMass getFull() { 12 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
102 return BlockMass(std::numeric_limits::max()); 12 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
103 } ----
104 ----
105 uint64_t getMass() const { return Mass; } 24 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
106 ----
107 bool isFull() const { return Mass == std::numeric_limits::max(); } 48 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
108 bool isEmpty() const { return !Mass; } 0

110 bool operator!() const { return isEmpty(); } ----

353 /// Unscaled probability weight. ----
354 /// ----
355 /// Probability weight for an edge in the graph (including the ----
356 /// successor/target node). ----
357 /// ----
358 /// All edges in the original function are 32-bit. However, exit edges from ----
359 /// loop packages are taken from 64-bit exit masses, so we need 64-bits of ----
360 /// space in general. ----
361 /// ----
362 /// In addition to the raw weight amount, Weight stores the type of the edge ----
363 /// in the current context (i.e., the context of the loop being processed). ----
364 /// Is this a local edge within the loop, an exit from the loop, or a ----
365 /// backedge to the loop header? ----

367 enum DistType { Local, Exit, Backedge }; ----
368 DistType Type = Local; ----
369 BlockNode TargetNode; ----
370 uint64_t Amount = 0; ----

375 }; ----

589 /// Graph of irreducible control flow. ----
590 /// ----
591 /// This graph is used for determining the SCCs in a loop (or top-level ----
592 /// function) that has irreducible control flow. ----
593 /// ----
594 /// During the block frequency algorithm, the local graphs are defined in a ----
595 /// light-weight way, deferring to the \a BasicBlock or \a MachineBasicBlock ----
596 /// graphs for most edges, but getting others from \a LoopData::ExitMap. The ----
597 /// latter only has successor information. ----
598 /// ----
599 /// \a IrreducibleGraph makes this graph explicit. It's in a form that can use ----
600 /// \a GraphTraits (so that \a analyzeIrreducible() can use \a scc_iterator), ----
601 /// and it explicitly lists predecessors and successors. The initialization ----
602 /// that relies on \c MachineBasicBlock is defined in the header. ----
603 struct IrreducibleGraph { ----
604 using BFIBase = BlockFrequencyInfoImplBase; ----
605 ----
606 BFIBase &BFI; ----
607 ----
608 using BlockNode = BFIBase::BlockNode; ----
609 struct IrrNode { ----
610 BlockNode Node; ----
611 unsigned NumIn = 0; ----
612 std::deque Edges; ----
613 ----
614 IrrNode(const BlockNode &Node) : Node(Node) {} 0
615 ----
616 using iterator = std::deque::const_iterator; ----
617 ----
618 iterator pred_begin() const { return Edges.begin(); } 0
619 iterator succ_begin() const { return Edges.begin() + NumIn; } 0
620 iterator pred_end() const { return succ_begin(); } 0
621 iterator succ_end() const { return Edges.end(); } 0
622 }; ----
623 BlockNode Start; ----
624 const IrrNode *StartIrr = nullptr; ----
625 std::vector Nodes; ----
626 SmallDenseMap Lookup; ----

628 /// Construct an explicit graph containing irreducible control flow. ----

631 /// top-level function, if \c OuterLoop is \c nullptr). Uses \c ----
632 /// addBlockEdges to add block successors that have not been packaged into ----
633 /// loops. ----
634 /// ----
635 /// \a BlockFrequencyInfoImpl::computeIrreducibleMass() is the only expected ----
636 /// user of this. ----
637 template ----
638 IrreducibleGraph(BFIBase &BFI, const BFIBase::LoopData *OuterLoop, 0
639 BlockEdgesAdder addBlockEdges) : BFI(BFI) { 0
640 initialize(OuterLoop, addBlockEdges); 0
641 } 0

645 BlockEdgesAdder addBlockEdges); ----

652 } 0

662 template ----
663 void IrreducibleGraph::initialize(const BFIBase::LoopData *OuterLoop, 0
664 BlockEdgesAdder addBlockEdges) { ----
665 if (OuterLoop) { 0
666 addNodesInLoop(*OuterLoop); 0
667 for (auto N : OuterLoop->Nodes) 0
668 addEdges(N, OuterLoop, addBlockEdges); 0
669 } else { ----
670 addNodesInFunction(); 0
671 for (uint32_t Index = 0; Index < BFI.Working.size(); ++Index) 0
672 addEdges(Index, OuterLoop, addBlockEdges); 0
673 } ----
674 StartIrr = Lookup[Start.Index]; 0
675 } 0

677 template ----
678 void IrreducibleGraph::addEdges(const BlockNode &Node, 0
679 const BFIBase::LoopData *OuterLoop, ----
680 BlockEdgesAdder addBlockEdges) { ----
681 auto L = Lookup.find(Node.Index); 0
682 if (L == Lookup.end()) 0
683 return; 0
684 IrrNode &Irr = *L->second; 0
685 const auto &Working = BFI.Working[Node.Index]; 0
686 ----
687 if (Working.isAPackage()) 0
688 for (const auto &I : Working.Loop->Exits) 0
689 addEdge(Irr, I.first, OuterLoop); 0
690 else ----
691 addBlockEdges(*this, Irr, OuterLoop); 0
692 } ----

696 /// Shared implementation for block frequency analysis. ----
697 /// ----
698 /// This is a shared implementation of BlockFrequencyInfo and ----
699 /// MachineBlockFrequencyInfo, and calculates the relative frequencies of ----
700 /// blocks. ----
701 /// ----
702 /// LoopInfo defines a loop as a "non-trivial" SCC dominated by a single block, ----
703 /// which is called the header. A given loop, L, can have sub-loops, which are ----
704 /// loops within the subgraph of L that exclude its header. (A "trivial" SCC ----
705 /// consists of a single block that does not have a self-edge.) ----
706 /// ----
707 /// In addition to loops, this algorithm has limited support for irreducible ----
708 /// SCCs, which are SCCs with multiple entry blocks. Irreducible SCCs are ----
709 /// discovered on the fly, and modelled as loops with multiple headers. ----
710 /// ----
711 /// The headers of irreducible sub-SCCs consist of its entry blocks and all ----
712 /// nodes that are targets of a backedge within it (excluding backedges within ----
713 /// true sub-loops). Block frequency calculations act as if a block is ----
714 /// inserted that intercepts all the edges to the headers. All backedges and ----
715 /// entries point to this block. Its successors are the headers, which split ----
716 /// the frequency evenly. ----
717 /// ----
718 /// This algorithm leverages BlockMass and ScaledNumber to maintain precision, ----
719 /// separates mass distribution from loop scaling, and dithers to eliminate ----
720 /// probability mass loss. ----
721 /// ----
722 /// The implementation is split between BlockFrequencyInfoImpl, which knows the ----
723 /// type of graph being modelled (BasicBlock vs. MachineBasicBlock), and ----
724 /// BlockFrequencyInfoImplBase, which doesn't. The base class uses \a ----
725 /// BlockNode, a wrapper around a uint32_t. BlockNode is numbered from 0 in ----
726 /// reverse-post order. This gives two advantages: it's easy to compare the ----
727 /// relative ordering of two nodes, and maps keyed on BlockT can be represented ----
728 /// by vectors. ----
729 /// ----
730 /// This algorithm is O(V+E), unless there is irreducible control flow, in ----
731 /// which case it's O(V*E) in the worst case. ----
732 /// ----
733 /// These are the main stages: ----
734 /// ----
735 /// 0. Reverse post-order traversal (\a initializeRPOT()). ----
736 /// ----
737 /// Run a single post-order traversal and save it (in reverse) in RPOT. ----
738 /// All other stages make use of this ordering. Save a lookup from BlockT ----
739 /// to BlockNode (the index into RPOT) in Nodes. ----
740 /// ----
741 /// 1. Loop initialization (\a initializeLoops()). ----
742 /// ----
743 /// Translate LoopInfo/MachineLoopInfo into a form suitable for the rest of ----
744 /// the algorithm. In particular, store the immediate members of each loop ----
745 /// in reverse post-order. ----
746 /// ----
747 /// 2. Calculate mass and scale in loops (\a computeMassInLoops()). ----
748 /// ----
749 /// For each loop (bottom-up), distribute mass through the DAG resulting ----
750 /// from ignoring backedges and treating sub-loops as a single pseudo-node. ----
751 /// Track the backedge mass distributed to the loop header, and use it to ----
752 /// calculate the loop scale (number of loop iterations). Immediate ----
753 /// members that represent sub-loops will already have been visited and ----
754 /// packaged into a pseudo-node. ----
755 /// ----
756 /// Distributing mass in a loop is a reverse-post-order traversal through ----
757 /// the loop. Start by assigning full mass to the Loop header. For each ----
758 /// node in the loop: ----
759 /// ----
760 /// - Fetch and categorize the weight distribution for its successors. ----
761 /// If this is a packaged-subloop, the weight distribution is stored ----
762 /// in \a LoopData::Exits. Otherwise, fetch it from ----
763 /// BranchProbabilityInfo. ----
764 /// ----
765 /// - Each successor is categorized as \a Weight::Local, a local edge ----
766 /// within the current loop, \a Weight::Backedge, a backedge to the ----
767 /// loop header, or \a Weight::Exit, any successor outside the loop. ----
768 /// The weight, the successor, and its category are stored in \a ----
769 /// Distribution. There can be multiple edges to each successor. ----
770 /// ----
771 /// - If there's a backedge to a non-header, there's an irreducible SCC. ----
772 /// The usual flow is temporarily aborted. \a ----
773 /// computeIrreducibleMass() finds the irreducible SCCs within the ----
774 /// loop, packages them up, and restarts the flow. ----
775 /// ----
776 /// - Normalize the distribution: scale weights down so that their sum ----
777 /// is 32-bits, and coalesce multiple edges to the same node. ----
778 /// ----
779 /// - Distribute the mass accordingly, dithering to minimize mass loss, ----
780 /// as described in \a distributeMass(). ----
781 /// ----
782 /// In the case of irreducible loops, instead of a single loop header, ----
783 /// there will be several. The computation of backedge masses is similar ----
784 /// but instead of having a single backedge mass, there will be one ----
785 /// backedge per loop header. In these cases, each backedge will carry ----
786 /// a mass proportional to the edge weights along the corresponding ----
787 /// path. ----
788 /// ----
789 /// At the end of propagation, the full mass assigned to the loop will be ----
790 /// distributed among the loop headers proportionally according to the ----
791 /// mass flowing through their backedges. ----
792 /// ----
793 /// Finally, calculate the loop scale from the accumulated backedge mass. ----
794 /// ----
795 /// 3. Distribute mass in the function (\a computeMassInFunction()). ----
796 /// ----
797 /// Finally, distribute mass through the DAG resulting from packaging all ----
798 /// loops in the function. This uses the same algorithm as distributing ----
799 /// mass in a loop, except that there are no exit or backedge edges. ----
800 /// ----
801 /// 4. Unpackage loops (\a unwrapLoops()). ----
802 /// ----
803 /// Initialize each block's frequency to a floating point representation of ----
804 /// its mass. ----
805 /// ----
806 /// Visit loops top-down, scaling the frequencies of its immediate members ----
807 /// by the loop's pseudo-node's frequency. ----
808 /// ----
809 /// 5. Convert frequencies to a 64-bit range (\a finalizeMetrics()). ----
810 /// ----
811 /// Using the min and max frequencies as a guide, translate floating point ----
812 /// frequencies to an appropriate range in uint64_t. ----
813 /// ----
814 /// It has some known flaws. ----
815 /// ----
816 /// - The model of irreducible control flow is a rough approximation. ----
817 /// ----
818 /// Modelling irreducible control flow exactly involves setting up and ----
819 /// solving a group of infinite geometric series. Such precision is ----
820 /// unlikely to be worthwhile, since most of our algorithms give up on ----
821 /// irreducible control flow anyway. ----
822 /// ----
823 /// Nevertheless, we might find that we need to get closer. Here's a sort ----
824 /// of TODO list for the model with diminishing returns, to be completed as ----
825 /// necessary. ----
826 /// ----
827 /// - The headers for the \a LoopData representing an irreducible SCC ----
828 /// include non-entry blocks. When these extra blocks exist, they ----
829 /// indicate a self-contained irreducible sub-SCC. We could treat them ----
830 /// as sub-loops, rather than arbitrarily shoving the problematic ----
831 /// blocks into the headers of the main irreducible SCC. ----
832 /// ----
833 /// - Entry frequencies are assumed to be evenly split between the ----
834 /// headers of a given irreducible SCC, which is the only option if we ----
835 /// need to compute mass in the SCC before its parent loop. Instead, ----
836 /// we could partially compute mass in the parent loop, and stop when ----
837 /// we get to the SCC. Here, we have the correct ratio of entry ----
838 /// masses, which we can use to adjust their relative frequencies. ----
839 /// Compute mass in the SCC, and then continue propagation in the ----
840 /// parent. ----
841 /// ----
842 /// - We can propagate mass iteratively through the SCC, for some fixed ----
843 /// number of iterations. Each iteration starts by assigning the entry ----
844 /// blocks their backedge mass from the prior iteration. The final ----
845 /// mass for each block (and each exit, and the total backedge mass ----
846 /// used for computing loop scale) is the sum of all iterations. ----
847 /// (Running this until fixed point would "solve" the geometric ----
848 /// series by simulation.) ----
849 template class BlockFrequencyInfoImpl : BlockFrequencyInfoImplBase { ----

971 /// The current implementation for computing relative block frequencies does ----
972 /// not handle correctly control-flow graphs containing irreducible loops. To ----
973 /// resolve the problem, we apply a post-processing step, which iteratively ----
974 /// updates block frequencies based on the frequencies of their predesessors. ----
975 /// This corresponds to finding the stationary point of the Markov chain by ----
976 /// an iterative method aka "PageRank computation". ----
977 /// The algorithm takes at most O(|E| * IterativeBFIMaxIterations) steps but ----
978 /// typically converges faster. ----
979 /// ----
980 /// Decide whether we want to apply iterative inference for a given function. ----
981 bool needIterativeInference() const; ----

984 void applyIterativeInference(); ----

1190 template void BlockFrequencyInfoImpl::initializeLoops() { 12 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1191 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "loop-detection\n"); 12 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1192 if (LI->empty()) 12 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1193 return; 12 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1194 ----
1195 // Visit loops top down and assign them an index. ----
1196 std::deque> Q; 0
1197 for (const LoopT *L : *LI) 0
1198 Q.emplace_back(L, nullptr); 0
1199 while (!Q.empty()) { 0
1200 const LoopT *Loop = Q.front().first; 0
1201 LoopData *Parent = Q.front().second; 0
1202 Q.pop_front(); 0
1203 ----
1204 BlockNode Header = getNode(Loop->getHeader()); 0
1205 assert(Header.isValid()); 0
1206 ----
1207 Loops.emplace_back(Parent, Header); 0
1208 Working[Header.Index].Loop = &Loops.back(); 0
1209 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " - loop = " << getBlockName(Header) << "\n"); 0
1210 ----
1211 for (const LoopT *L : *Loop) 0
1212 Q.emplace_back(L, &Loops.back()); 0
1213 } ----
1214 ----
1215 // Visit nodes in reverse post-order and add them to their deepest containing ----
1216 // loop. ----
1217 for (size_t Index = 0; Index < RPOT.size(); ++Index) { 0
1218 // Loop headers have already been mostly mapped. ----
1219 if (Working[Index].isLoopHeader()) { 0
1220 LoopData *ContainingLoop = Working[Index].getContainingLoop(); 0
1221 if (ContainingLoop) 0
1222 ContainingLoop->Nodes.push_back(Index); 0
1223 continue; 0
1224 } 0
1225 ----
1226 const LoopT *Loop = LI->getLoopFor(RPOT[Index]); 0
1227 if (!Loop) 0
1228 continue; 0
1229 ----
1230 // Add this node to its containing loop's member list. ----
1231 BlockNode Header = getNode(Loop->getHeader()); 0
1232 assert(Header.isValid()); 0
1233 const auto &HeaderData = Working[Header.Index]; 0
1234 assert(HeaderData.isLoopHeader()); 0
1235 ----
1236 Working[Index].Loop = HeaderData.Loop; 0
1237 HeaderData.Loop->Nodes.push_back(Index); 0
1238 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " - loop = " << getBlockName(Header) 0
1239 << ": member = " << getBlockName(Index) << "\n"); ----
1240 } ----
1241 } 0

1243 template void BlockFrequencyInfoImpl::computeMassInLoops() { 12 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1244 // Visit loops with the deepest first, and the top-level loops last. ----
1245 for (auto L = Loops.rbegin(), E = Loops.rend(); L != E; ++L) { 12 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1246 if (computeMassInLoop(*L)) 0
1247 continue; 0
1248 auto Next = std::next(L); 0
1249 computeIrreducibleMass(&*L, L.base()); 0
1250 L = std::prev(Next); 0
1251 if (computeMassInLoop(*L)) 0
1252 continue; 0
1253 llvm_unreachable("unhandled irreducible control flow"); 0
1254 } ----
1255 } 12 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll
1256 ----
1257 template ----
1258 bool BlockFrequencyInfoImpl::computeMassInLoop(LoopData &Loop) { 0
1259 // Compute mass in loop. ----
1260 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "compute-mass-in-loop: " << getLoopName(Loop) << "\n"); 0
1261 ----
1262 if (Loop.isIrreducible()) { 0
1263 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "isIrreducible = true\n"); 0
1264 Distribution Dist; 0
1265 unsigned NumHeadersWithWeight = 0; 0
1266 std::optional MinHeaderWeight; 0
1267 DenseSet HeadersWithoutWeight; 0
1268 HeadersWithoutWeight.reserve(Loop.NumHeaders); 0
1269 for (uint32_t H = 0; H < Loop.NumHeaders; ++H) { 0
1270 auto &HeaderNode = Loop.Nodes[H]; 0
1271 const BlockT *Block = getBlock(HeaderNode); 0
1272 IsIrrLoopHeader.set(Loop.Nodes[H].Index); 0
1273 std::optional HeaderWeight = Block->getIrrLoopHeaderWeight(); 0
1274 if (!HeaderWeight) { 0
1275 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Missing irr loop header metadata on " 0
1276 << getBlockName(HeaderNode) << "\n"); ----
1277 HeadersWithoutWeight.insert(H); 0
1278 continue; 0
1279 } ----
1280 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << getBlockName(HeaderNode) 0
1281 << " has irr loop header weight " << *HeaderWeight ----
1282 << "\n"); ----
1283 NumHeadersWithWeight++; 0
1284 uint64_t HeaderWeightValue = *HeaderWeight; 0
1285 if (!MinHeaderWeight || HeaderWeightValue < MinHeaderWeight) 0
1286 MinHeaderWeight = HeaderWeightValue; 0
1287 if (HeaderWeightValue) { 0
1288 Dist.addLocal(HeaderNode, HeaderWeightValue); 0
1289 } ----
1290 } ----
1291 // As a heuristic, if some headers don't have a weight, give them the ----
1292 // minimum weight seen (not to disrupt the existing trends too much by ----
1293 // using a weight that's in the general range of the other headers' weights, ----
1294 // and the minimum seems to perform better than the average.) ----
1295 // FIXME: better update in the passes that drop the header weight. ----
1296 // If no headers have a weight, give them even weight (use weight 1). ----
1297 if (!MinHeaderWeight) 0
1298 MinHeaderWeight = 1; 0
1299 for (uint32_t H : HeadersWithoutWeight) { 0
1300 auto &HeaderNode = Loop.Nodes[H]; 0
1301 assert(!getBlock(HeaderNode)->getIrrLoopHeaderWeight() && 0
1302 "Shouldn't have a weight metadata"); ----
1303 uint64_t MinWeight = *MinHeaderWeight; 0
1304 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Giving weight " << MinWeight << " to " 0
1305 << getBlockName(HeaderNode) << "\n"); ----
1306 if (MinWeight) 0
1307 Dist.addLocal(HeaderNode, MinWeight); 0
1308 } ----
1309 distributeIrrLoopHeaderMass(Dist); 0
1310 for (const BlockNode &M : Loop.Nodes) 0
1311 if (!propagateMassToSuccessors(&Loop, M)) 0
1312 llvm_unreachable("unhandled irreducible control flow"); 0
1313 if (NumHeadersWithWeight == 0) 0
1314 // No headers have a metadata. Adjust header mass. ----
1315 adjustLoopHeaderMass(Loop); 0
1316 } else { 0
1317 Working[Loop.getHeader().Index].getMass() = BlockMass::getFull(); 0
1318 if (!propagateMassToSuccessors(&Loop, Loop.getHeader())) 0
1319 llvm_unreachable("irreducible control flow to loop header!?"); 0
1320 for (const BlockNode &M : Loop.members()) 0
1321 if (!propagateMassToSuccessors(&Loop, M)) 0
1322 // Irreducible backedge. ----
1323 return false; 0
1324 } ----
1325 ----
1326 computeLoopScale(Loop); 0
1327 packageLoop(Loop); 0
1328 return true; 0
1329 } ----

1337 ----

1361 bool BlockFrequencyInfoImpl::needIterativeInference() const { 12 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll

1364 if (!F->getFunction().hasProfileData()) 0

1366 // Apply iterative inference only if the function contains irreducible loops; ----
1367 // otherwise, computed block frequencies are reasonably correct. ----
1368 for (auto L = Loops.rbegin(), E = Loops.rend(); L != E; ++L) { 0
1369 if (L->isIrreducible()) 0

1374 ----
1375 template void BlockFrequencyInfoImpl::applyIterativeInference() { 0
1376 // Extract blocks for processing: a block is considered for inference iff it ----
1377 // can be reached from the entry by edges with a positive probability. ----
1378 // Non-processed blocks are assigned with the zero frequency and are ignored ----
1379 // in the computation ----
1380 std::vector ReachableBlocks; 0
1381 findReachableBlocks(ReachableBlocks); 0
1382 if (ReachableBlocks.empty()) 0
1383 return; 0
1384 ----
1385 // The map is used to to index successors/predecessors of reachable blocks in ----
1386 // the ReachableBlocks vector ----
1387 DenseMap BlockIndex; 0
1388 // Extract initial frequencies for the reachable blocks ----
1389 auto Freq = std::vector(ReachableBlocks.size()); 0
1390 Scaled64 SumFreq; 0
1391 for (size_t I = 0; I < ReachableBlocks.size(); I++) { 0
1392 const BlockT *BB = ReachableBlocks[I]; 0
1393 BlockIndex[BB] = I; 0
1394 Freq[I] = getFloatingBlockFreq(BB); 0
1395 SumFreq += Freq[I]; 0
1396 } ----
1397 assert(!SumFreq.isZero() && "empty initial block frequencies"); 0
1398 ----
1399 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "Applying iterative inference for " << F->getName() 0
1400 << " with " << ReachableBlocks.size() << " blocks\n"); ----
1401 ----
1402 // Normalizing frequencies so they sum up to 1.0 ----
1403 for (auto &Value : Freq) { 0
1404 Value /= SumFreq; 0
1405 } ----
1406 ----
1407 // Setting up edge probabilities using sparse matrix representation: ----
1408 // ProbMatrix[I] holds a vector of pairs (J, P) where Pr[J -> I | J] = P ----
1409 ProbMatrixType ProbMatrix; 0
1410 initTransitionProbabilities(ReachableBlocks, BlockIndex, ProbMatrix); 0
1411 ----
1412 // Run the propagation ----
1413 iterativeInference(ProbMatrix, Freq); 0
1414 ----
1415 // Assign computed frequency values ----
1416 for (const BlockT &BB : *F) { 0
1417 auto Node = getNode(&BB); 0
1418 if (!Node.isValid()) 0
1419 continue; 0
1420 if (BlockIndex.count(&BB)) { 0
1421 Freqs[Node.Index].Scaled = Freq[BlockIndex[&BB]]; 0
1422 } else { ----
1423 Freqs[Node.Index].Scaled = Scaled64::getZero(); 0
1424 } ----
1425 } ----
1426 } 0
1427 ----
1428 template ----
1429 void BlockFrequencyInfoImpl::iterativeInference( 0
1430 const ProbMatrixType &ProbMatrix, std::vector &Freq) const { ----
1431 assert(0.0 < IterativeBFIPrecision && IterativeBFIPrecision < 1.0 && 0
1432 "incorrectly specified precision"); ----
1433 // Convert double precision to Scaled64 ----
1434 const auto Precision = ----
1435 Scaled64::getInverse(static_cast(1.0 / IterativeBFIPrecision)); 0
1436 const size_t MaxIterations = IterativeBFIMaxIterationsPerBlock * Freq.size(); 0
1437 ----
1438 #ifndef NDEBUG ----
1439 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " Initial discrepancy = " 0
1440 << discrepancy(ProbMatrix, Freq).toString() << "\n"); ----
1441 #endif ----
1442 ----
1443 // Successors[I] holds unique sucessors of the I-th block ----
1444 auto Successors = std::vector>(Freq.size()); 0
1445 for (size_t I = 0; I < Freq.size(); I++) { 0
1446 for (const auto &Jump : ProbMatrix[I]) { 0
1447 Successors[Jump.first].push_back(I); 0
1448 } ----
1449 } ----
1450 ----
1451 // To speedup computation, we maintain a set of "active" blocks whose ----
1452 // frequencies need to be updated based on the incoming edges. ----
1453 // The set is dynamic and changes after every update. Initially all blocks ----
1454 // with a positive frequency are active ----
1455 auto IsActive = BitVector(Freq.size(), false); 0
1456 std::queue ActiveSet; 0
1457 for (size_t I = 0; I < Freq.size(); I++) { 0
1458 if (Freq[I] > 0) { 0
1459 ActiveSet.push(I); 0
1460 IsActive[I] = true; 0
1461 } ----
1462 } ----
1463 ----
1464 // Iterate over the blocks propagating frequencies ----
1465 size_t It = 0; 0
1466 while (It++ < MaxIterations && !ActiveSet.empty()) { 0
1467 size_t I = ActiveSet.front(); 0
1468 ActiveSet.pop(); 0
1469 IsActive[I] = false; 0
1470 ----
1471 // Compute a new frequency for the block: NewFreq := Freq \times ProbMatrix. ----
1472 // A special care is taken for self-edges that needs to be scaled by ----
1473 // (1.0 - SelfProb), where SelfProb is the sum of probabilities on the edges ----
1474 Scaled64 NewFreq; 0
1475 Scaled64 OneMinusSelfProb = Scaled64::getOne(); 0
1476 for (const auto &Jump : ProbMatrix[I]) { 0
1477 if (Jump.first == I) { 0
1478 OneMinusSelfProb -= Jump.second; 0
1479 } else { ----
1480 NewFreq += Freq[Jump.first] * Jump.second; 0
1481 } ----
1482 } ----
1483 if (OneMinusSelfProb != Scaled64::getOne()) 0
1484 NewFreq /= OneMinusSelfProb; 0
1485 ----
1486 // If the block's frequency has changed enough, then ----
1487 // make sure the block and its successors are in the active set ----
1488 auto Change = Freq[I] >= NewFreq ? Freq[I] - NewFreq : NewFreq - Freq[I]; 0
1489 if (Change > Precision) { 0
1490 ActiveSet.push(I); 0
1491 IsActive[I] = true; 0
1492 for (size_t Succ : Successors[I]) { 0
1493 if (!IsActive[Succ]) { 0
1494 ActiveSet.push(Succ); 0
1495 IsActive[Succ] = true; 0
1496 } ----
1497 } ----
1498 } ----
1499 ----
1500 // Update the frequency for the block ----
1501 Freq[I] = NewFreq; 0
1502 } ----
1503 ----
1504 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " Completed " << It << " inference iterations" 0
1505 << format(" (%0.0f per block)", double(It) / Freq.size()) ----
1506 << "\n"); ----
1507 #ifndef NDEBUG ----
1508 LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << " Final discrepancy = " 0
1509 << discrepancy(ProbMatrix, Freq).toString() << "\n"); ----
1510 #endif ----
1511 } 0
1512 ----
1513 template ----
1514 void BlockFrequencyInfoImpl::findReachableBlocks( 0
1515 std::vector &Blocks) const { ----
1516 // Find all blocks to apply inference on, that is, reachable from the entry ----
1517 // along edges with non-zero probablities ----
1518 std::queue Queue; 0
1519 SmallPtrSet Reachable; 0
1520 const BlockT *Entry = &F->front(); 0
1521 Queue.push(Entry); 0
1522 Reachable.insert(Entry); 0
1523 while (!Queue.empty()) { 0
1524 const BlockT *SrcBB = Queue.front(); 0
1525 Queue.pop(); 0
1526 for (const BlockT *DstBB : children(SrcBB)) { 0
1527 auto EP = BPI->getEdgeProbability(SrcBB, DstBB); 0
1528 if (EP.isZero()) 0
1529 continue; 0
1530 if (Reachable.insert(DstBB).second) 0
1531 Queue.push(DstBB); 0
1532 } ----
1533 } ----
1534 ----
1535 // Find all blocks to apply inference on, that is, backward reachable from ----
1536 // the entry along (backward) edges with non-zero probablities ----
1537 SmallPtrSet InverseReachable; 0
1538 for (const BlockT &BB : *F) { 0
1539 // An exit block is a block without any successors ----
1540 bool HasSucc = GraphTraits::child_begin(&BB) != 0
1541 GraphTraits::child_end(&BB); 0
1542 if (!HasSucc && Reachable.count(&BB)) { 0
1543 Queue.push(&BB); 0
1544 InverseReachable.insert(&BB); 0
1545 } ----
1546 } ----
1547 while (!Queue.empty()) { 0
1548 const BlockT *SrcBB = Queue.front(); 0
1549 Queue.pop(); 0
1550 for (const BlockT *DstBB : children>(SrcBB)) { 0
1551 auto EP = BPI->getEdgeProbability(DstBB, SrcBB); 0
1552 if (EP.isZero()) 0
1553 continue; 0
1554 if (InverseReachable.insert(DstBB).second) 0
1555 Queue.push(DstBB); 0
1556 } ----
1557 } ----
1558 ----
1559 // Collect the result ----
1560 Blocks.reserve(F->size()); 0
1561 for (const BlockT &BB : *F) { 0
1562 if (Reachable.count(&BB) && InverseReachable.count(&BB)) { 0
1563 Blocks.push_back(&BB); 0
1564 } ----
1565 } ----
1566 } 0
1567 ----
1568 template ----
1569 void BlockFrequencyInfoImpl::initTransitionProbabilities( 0
1570 const std::vector &Blocks, ----
1571 const DenseMap &BlockIndex, ----
1572 ProbMatrixType &ProbMatrix) const { ----
1573 const size_t NumBlocks = Blocks.size(); 0
1574 auto Succs = std::vector>>(NumBlocks); 0
1575 auto SumProb = std::vector(NumBlocks); 0
1576 ----
1577 // Find unique successors and corresponding probabilities for every block ----
1578 for (size_t Src = 0; Src < NumBlocks; Src++) { 0
1579 const BlockT *BB = Blocks[Src]; 0
1580 SmallPtrSet UniqueSuccs; 0
1581 for (const auto SI : children(BB)) { 0
1582 // Ignore cold blocks ----
1583 if (BlockIndex.find(SI) == BlockIndex.end()) 0
1584 continue; 0
1585 // Ignore parallel edges between BB and SI blocks ----
1586 if (!UniqueSuccs.insert(SI).second) 0
1587 continue; 0
1588 // Ignore jumps with zero probability ----
1589 auto EP = BPI->getEdgeProbability(BB, SI); 0
1590 if (EP.isZero()) 0
1591 continue; 0
1592 ----
1593 auto EdgeProb = ----
1594 Scaled64::getFraction(EP.getNumerator(), EP.getDenominator()); 0
1595 size_t Dst = BlockIndex.find(SI)->second; 0
1596 Succs[Src].push_back(std::make_pair(Dst, EdgeProb)); 0
1597 SumProb[Src] += EdgeProb; 0
1598 } ----
1599 } ----
1600 ----
1601 // Add transitions for every jump with positive branch probability ----
1602 ProbMatrix = ProbMatrixType(NumBlocks); 0
1603 for (size_t Src = 0; Src < NumBlocks; Src++) { 0
1604 // Ignore blocks w/o successors ----
1605 if (Succs[Src].empty()) 0
1606 continue; 0
1607 ----
1608 assert(!SumProb[Src].isZero() && "Zero sum probability of non-exit block"); 0
1609 for (auto &Jump : Succs[Src]) { 0
1610 size_t Dst = Jump.first; 0
1611 Scaled64 Prob = Jump.second; 0
1612 ProbMatrix[Dst].push_back(std::make_pair(Src, Prob / SumProb[Src])); 0
1613 } ----
1614 } ----
1615 ----
1616 // Add transitions from sinks to the source ----
1617 size_t EntryIdx = BlockIndex.find(&F->front())->second; 0
1618 for (size_t Src = 0; Src < NumBlocks; Src++) { 0
1619 if (Succs[Src].empty()) { 0
1620 ProbMatrix[EntryIdx].push_back(std::make_pair(Src, Scaled64::getOne())); 0
1621 } ----
1622 } ----
1623 } 0
1624 ----
1625 #ifndef NDEBUG ----
1626 template ----
1627 BlockFrequencyInfoImplBase::Scaled64 BlockFrequencyInfoImpl::discrepancy( 0
1628 const ProbMatrixType &ProbMatrix, const std::vector &Freq) const { ----
1629 assert(Freq[0] > 0 && "Incorrectly computed frequency of the entry block"); 0
1630 Scaled64 Discrepancy; 0
1631 for (size_t I = 0; I < ProbMatrix.size(); I++) { 0
1632 Scaled64 Sum; 0
1633 for (const auto &Jump : ProbMatrix[I]) { 0
1634 Sum += Freq[Jump.first] * Jump.second; 0
1635 } ----

1639 return Discrepancy / Freq[0]; 0

1749 void BlockFrequencyInfoImpl::verifyMatch( 0
1750 BlockFrequencyInfoImpl &Other) const { ----
1751 bool Match = true; 0
1752 DenseMap ValidNodes; 0
1753 DenseMap OtherValidNodes; 0
1754 for (auto &Entry : Nodes) { 0

1762 if (BB) { 0

1764 } ----
1765 } ----

1767 unsigned NumOtherValidNodes = OtherValidNodes.size(); 0
1768 if (NumValidNodes != NumOtherValidNodes) { 0
1769 Match = false; 0
1770 dbgs() << "Number of blocks mismatch: " << NumValidNodes << " vs " 0
1771 << NumOtherValidNodes << "\n"; 0
1772 } else { ----
1773 for (auto &Entry : ValidNodes) { 0
1774 const BlockT *BB = Entry.first; 0
1775 BlockNode Node = Entry.second; 0
1776 if (OtherValidNodes.count(BB)) { 0
1777 BlockNode OtherNode = OtherValidNodes[BB]; 0
1778 const auto &Freq = Freqs[Node.Index]; 0
1779 const auto &OtherFreq = Other.Freqs[OtherNode.Index]; 0
1780 if (Freq.Integer != OtherFreq.Integer) { 0
1781 Match = false; 0
1782 dbgs() << "Freq mismatch: " << bfi_detail::getBlockName(BB) << " " 0
1783 << Freq.Integer << " vs " << OtherFreq.Integer << "\n"; 0
1784 } ----
1785 } else { ----
1786 Match = false; 0
1787 dbgs() << "Block " << bfi_detail::getBlockName(BB) << " index " 0
1788 << Node.Index << " does not exist in Other.\n"; 0
1789 } ----
1790 } ----
1791 // If there's a valid node in OtherValidNodes that's not in ValidNodes, ----
1792 // either the above num check or the check on OtherValidNodes will fail. ----
1793 } ----
1794 if (!Match) { 0
1795 dbgs() << "This\n"; 0
1796 print(dbgs()); 0
1797 dbgs() << "Other\n"; 0
1798 Other.print(dbgs()); 0
1799 } ----
1800 assert(Match && "BFI mismatch"); 0
1801 } 0

1806 enum GVDAGType { GVDT_None, GVDT_Fraction, GVDT_Integer, GVDT_Count }; ----

1809 struct BFIDOTGraphTraitsBase : public DefaultDOTGraphTraits { ----
1810 using GTraits = GraphTraits; ----
1811 using NodeRef = typename GTraits::NodeRef; ----
1812 using EdgeIter = typename GTraits::ChildIteratorType; ----
1813 using NodeIter = typename GTraits::nodes_iterator; ----
1814 ----
1815 uint64_t MaxFrequency = 0; ----
1816 ----
1817 explicit BFIDOTGraphTraitsBase(bool isSimple = false) 0
1818 : DefaultDOTGraphTraits(isSimple) {} 0
1819 ----
1820 static StringRef getGraphName(const BlockFrequencyInfoT *G) { 0
1821 return G->getFunction()->getName(); 0
1822 } ----
1823 ----
1824 std::string getNodeAttributes(NodeRef Node, const BlockFrequencyInfoT *Graph, 0
1825 unsigned HotPercentThreshold = 0) { ----
1826 std::string Result; 0
1827 if (!HotPercentThreshold) 0
1828 return Result; 0
1829 ----
1830 // Compute MaxFrequency on the fly: ----
1831 if (!MaxFrequency) { 0
1832 for (NodeIter I = GTraits::nodes_begin(Graph), 0
1833 E = GTraits::nodes_end(Graph); 0
1834 I != E; ++I) { 0
1835 NodeRef N = *I; 0
1836 MaxFrequency = 0
1837 std::max(MaxFrequency, Graph->getBlockFreq(N).getFrequency()); 0
1838 } ----
1839 } ----
1840 BlockFrequency Freq = Graph->getBlockFreq(Node); 0
1841 BlockFrequency HotFreq = ----
1842 (BlockFrequency(MaxFrequency) * 0
1843 BranchProbability::getBranchProbability(HotPercentThreshold, 100)); ----
1844 ----
1845 if (Freq < HotFreq) 0
1846 return Result; 0
1847 ----
1848 raw_string_ostream OS(Result); 0
1849 OS << "color=\"red\""; 0
1850 OS.flush(); 0
1851 return Result; 0
1852 } 0
1853 ----
1854 std::string getNodeLabel(NodeRef Node, const BlockFrequencyInfoT *Graph, 0
1855 GVDAGType GType, int layout_order = -1) { ----
1856 std::string Result; 0
1857 raw_string_ostream OS(Result); 0
1858 ----
1859 if (layout_order != -1) 0
1860 OS << Node->getName() << "[" << layout_order << "] : "; 0
1861 else ----
1862 OS << Node->getName() << " : "; 0
1863 switch (GType) { 0
1864 case GVDT_Fraction: 0
1865 Graph->printBlockFreq(OS, Node); 0
1866 break; 0
1867 case GVDT_Integer: 0
1868 OS << Graph->getBlockFreq(Node).getFrequency(); 0
1869 break; 0
1870 case GVDT_Count: { 0
1871 auto Count = Graph->getBlockProfileCount(Node); 0
1872 if (Count) 0
1873 OS << *Count; 0
1874 else ----
1875 OS << "Unknown"; 0
1876 break; 0
1877 } ----
1878 case GVDT_None: 0
1879 llvm_unreachable("If we are not supposed to render a graph we should " 0
1880 "never reach this point."); ----
1881 } ----
1882 return Result; 0
1883 } 0
1884 ----
1885 std::string getEdgeAttributes(NodeRef Node, EdgeIter EI, 0
1886 const BlockFrequencyInfoT *BFI, ----
1887 const BranchProbabilityInfoT *BPI, ----
1888 unsigned HotPercentThreshold = 0) { ----
1889 std::string Str; 0
1890 if (!BPI) 0
1891 return Str; 0
1892 ----
1893 BranchProbability BP = BPI->getEdgeProbability(Node, EI); 0
1894 uint32_t N = BP.getNumerator(); 0
1895 uint32_t D = BP.getDenominator(); 0
1896 double Percent = 100.0 * N / D; 0
1897 raw_string_ostream OS(Str); 0
1898 OS << format("label=\"%.1f%%\"", Percent); 0
1899 ----
1900 if (HotPercentThreshold) { 0
1901 BlockFrequency EFreq = BFI->getBlockFreq(Node) * BP; 0
1902 BlockFrequency HotFreq = BlockFrequency(MaxFrequency) * 0
1903 BranchProbability(HotPercentThreshold, 100); ----
1904 ----
1905 if (EFreq >= HotFreq) { 0
1906 OS << ",color=\"red\""; 0
1907 } ----
1908 } ----
1909 ----
1910 OS.flush(); 0
1911 return Str; 0
1912 } 0
